5|$|In {{the early}} 1990s the {{government}} reined in inflation {{by making the}} peso equal in value to the U.S. dollar, and privatised numerous state-run companies, using part of the proceeds to reduce the <b>national</b> <b>debt.</b> However, a sustained recession {{at the turn of}} the 21st century culminated in a default, and the government again devalued the peso. By 2005 the economy had recovered, but a judicial ruling originating from the previous crisis led to a new default in 2014.|$|E
