50|$|Paying {{interest}} on outstanding bonds means tax rates will be higher, but <b>national</b> <b>debts</b> have an advantage: {{they can be}} extremely useful for conducting monetary policy. When a central bank would like to increase the money supply, it can merely purchase previously-issued bonds. When it would like to contract the money supply, it can sell them. This {{is known as the}} secondary market, but for this to work, the bonds, of course, have to have been issued previously in the primary market.|$|R
